# 5.4 Special Coordination

Special coordination covers non-standard, priority, or abnormal situations requiring enhanced communication between units.

---

## 5.4.1 General Principles

Special coordination shall be applied when standard procedures are insufficient to ensure safety or efficiency.

Controllers must:

– Prioritise safety above all else  
– Clearly communicate intentions  
– Confirm all critical information  
– Coordinate early and explicitly  

---

## 5.4.2 Priority Aircraft

Priority shall be given to:

– Aircraft declaring an emergency (MAYDAY / PAN PAN)  
– Aircraft with medical emergencies onboard  
– Aircraft with low fuel or operational urgency  
– Aircraft conducting security or military operations  

The Tower controller must:

– Provide immediate handling priority  
– Expedite clearances and instructions  
– Inform and coordinate with all relevant units  

Example:

```text
GFA789, priority landing approved, runway 27, wind 270 degrees 8 knots, cleared to land.
```

---

## 5.4.3 Emergency Coordination

In an emergency situation, the controller must:

– Acknowledge the emergency  
– Obtain essential information (nature, intentions, fuel, souls on board if required)  
– Coordinate with Approach and other units  
– Ensure the runway is available  

Additional actions:

– Suspend normal operations if required  
– Keep communications concise and clear  
– Monitor the aircraft continuously  

Example:

```text
GFA789, roger MAYDAY, runway 27, cleared to land, wind 270 degrees 8 knots.
```

---

## 5.4.4 Opposite Direction Operations

Opposite direction operations may be used when:

– Required for operational reasons  
– Wind conditions favour an alternative runway direction  
– Traffic permits safe execution  

The controller must:

– Ensure no conflicting traffic exists  
– Coordinate with Approach where applicable  
– Clearly inform all affected aircraft  

Example:

```text
GFA123, runway 09, cleared for takeoff, opposite direction traffic in operation.
```

---

## 5.4.5 Runway Closure and Restrictions

If a runway becomes unavailable:

– Immediately suspend all clearances  
– Inform all aircraft on frequency  
– Coordinate with Approach and adjacent units  

The controller must:

– Issue alternative instructions  
– Re-sequence traffic as required  
– Provide delay or diversion information if necessary  

Example:

```text
All stations, runway 27 closed, standby for further instructions.
```

---

## 5.4.6 Low Visibility Operations (LVP)

During reduced visibility conditions, controllers must:

– Increase spacing between aircraft  
– Protect critical areas (e.g. ILS sensitive areas)  
– Ensure strict adherence to procedures  

Additional considerations:

– Minimise runway occupancy time  
– Avoid conditional clearances where possible  
– Maintain precise phraseology  

---

## 5.4.7 Multiple Go-Around Situations

When multiple go-arounds occur:

– Re-establish sequencing immediately  
– Coordinate with Approach  
– Avoid compounding conflicts  

The controller must:

– Maintain awareness of all aircraft positions  
– Issue clear and simple instructions  
– Prioritise stabilising the situation  

---

## 5.4.8 Non-Routine Traffic

Non-routine traffic includes:

– VFR transits through controlled airspace  
– Training flights and circuits  
– Helicopter operations  
– Military or special flights  

The controller must:

– Integrate traffic safely with IFR operations  
– Apply appropriate separation  
– Provide clear instructions tailored to aircraft type  

---

## 5.4.9 Key Principles

Special coordination requires:

– Early recognition of non-standard situations  
– Clear and concise communication  
– Strong situational awareness  
– Decisive and timely action  

Controllers must:

– Avoid ambiguity  
– Confirm coordination outcomes  
– Adapt to changing situations  
– Maintain control of the overall traffic picture  

Failure to apply effective special coordination may result in:

– Loss of separation  
– Increased workload  
– Traffic inefficiency  
– Reduced safety margins  
